# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sweep-line-paradigm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] For a set A of objects in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , the cells in the arrangement are the connected components of sets of the form $(\cap X)\setminus \cup (A\setminus X)$ for subsets X of A .
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] That is, for each X the cells are the connected components of the points that belong to every object in X and do not belong to any other object.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] Of particular interest are the arrangements of lines and arrangements of hyperplanes.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] More generally, geometers have studied arrangements of other types of curves in the plane, and of other more complicated types of surface.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] An interest in the study of arrangements was driven by advances in computational geometry, where the arrangements were unifying structures for many problems.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/arrangement-space-partition] Advances in study of more complicated objects, such as algebraic surfaces, contributed to "real-world" applications, such as motion planning and computer vision.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] Early algorithms for Boolean operations on polygons were based on the use of bitmaps.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] Using bitmaps in modeling polygon shapes has many drawbacks.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] One of the drawbacks is that the memory usage can be very large, since the resolution of polygons is proportional to the number of bits used to represent polygons.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] The higher the resolution is desired, the more the number of bits is required.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] Modern implementations for Boolean operations on polygons tend to use plane sweep algorithms (or Sweep line algorithms).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] A list of papers using plane sweep algorithms for Boolean operations on polygons can be found in References below.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/boolean-operations-on-polygons] Boolean operations on convex polygons and monotone polygons of the same direction may be performed in linear time.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] In computing, an **event** is a detectable occurrence or change in state that the system is designed to monitor, such as user input, hardware interrupt, system notification, or change in data or conditions.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] When associated with an event handler, an event triggers a response.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] The handler may run synchronously, where the execution thread is blocked until the event handler completes its processing, or asynchronously, where the event may be processed later.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Even when synchronous handling appears to block execution, the underlying mechanism in many systems is still asynchronous, managed by the event loop.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Events can be implemented through various mechanisms such as callbacks, message objects, signals, or interrupts, and events themselves are distinct from the implementation mechanisms used.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Event propagation models, such as bubbling, capturing, and pub/sub, define how events are distributed and handled within a system.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Other key aspects include event loops, event queueing and prioritization, event sourcing, and complex event processing patterns.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] These mechanisms contribute to the flexibility and scalability of event-driven systems.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] In distributed systems, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] In computer science, an **event** (also called **event semaphore**) is a type of synchronization mechanism that is used to indicate to waiting processes when a particular condition has become true.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Different implementations of events may provide different subsets of these possible operations; for example, the implementation provided by Microsoft Windows provides the operations **wait** (WaitForObject and related functions), **set** (SetEvent), and **clear** (ResetEvent).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] An option that may be specified during creation of the event object changes the behaviour of SetEvent so that only a single thread is released and the state is automatically returned to false after that thread is released.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Events short of **reset** function, that is, those which can be completed only once, are known as futures.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/event-computing] Monitors are, on the other hand, more general since they combine completion signaling with mutex and do not let the producer and consumer to execute simultaneously in the monitor making it an event+critical section.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In computational geometry, **Klee's measure problem** is the problem of determining how efficiently the measure of a union of (multidimensional) rectangular ranges can be computed.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Here, a *d*-dimensional rectangular range is defined to be a Cartesian product of *d* intervals of real numbers, which is a subset of **R***d*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] The problem is named after Victor Klee, who gave an algorithm for computing the length of a union of intervals (the case *d* = 1) which was later shown to be optimally efficient in the sense of computational complexity theory.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] The computational complexity of computing the area of a union of 2-dimensional rectangular ranges is now also known, but the case *d* ≥ 3 remains an open problem.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In 1977, Victor Klee considered the following problem: given a collection of *n* intervals in the real line, compute the length of their union.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] He then presented an algorithm to solve this problem with computational complexity (or "running time") $O(n\log n)$ — see Big O notation for the meaning of this statement.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] This algorithm, based on sorting the intervals, was later shown by Michael Fredman and Bruce Weide (1978) to be optimal.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Later in 1977, Jon Bentley considered a 2-dimensional analogue of this problem: given a collection of *n* rectangles, find the area of their union.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] He also obtained a complexity $O(n\log n)$ algorithm, now known as **Bentley's algorithm**, based on reducing the problem to *n* *1*-dimensional problems: this is done by sweeping a vertical line across the area.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Using this method, the area of the union can be computed without explicitly constructing the union itself.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Bentley's algorithm is now also known to be optimal (in the 2-dimensional case), and is used in computer graphics, among other areas.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] These two problems are the 1- and 2-dimensional cases of a more general question: given a collection of *n* *d*-dimensional rectangular ranges, compute the measure of their union.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] This general problem is Klee's measure problem.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] When generalized to the *d*-dimensional case, Bentley's algorithm has a running time of $O(n^{d-1}\log n)$ .
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] This turns out *not* to be optimal, because it only decomposes the *d*-dimensional problem into *n* (*d-1*)-dimensional problems, and does not further decompose those subproblems.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In 1981, Jan van Leeuwen and Derek Wood improved the running time of this algorithm to $O(n^{d-1})$ for *d* ≥ 3 by using dynamic quadtrees.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In 1988, Mark Overmars and Chee Yap proposed an $O(n^{d/2}\log n)$ algorithm for *d* ≥ 3.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Their algorithm uses a particular data structure similar to a kd-tree to decompose the problem into 2-dimensional components and aggregate those components efficiently; the 2-dimensional problems themselves are solved efficiently using a trellis structure.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Although asymptotically faster than Bentley's algorithm, its data structures use significantly more space, so it is only used in problems where either *n* or *d* is large.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In 1998, Bogdan Chlebus proposed a simpler algorithm with the same asymptotic running time for the common special cases where *d* is 3 or 4.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Chan developed a simpler algorithm that avoids the need for dynamic data structures and eliminates the logarithmic factor, lowering the best known running time for d ≥ 3 to $O(n^{d/2})$ .
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] The only known lower bound for any *d* is $\Omega (n\log n)$ , and optimal algorithms with this running time are known for *d*=1 and *d*=2.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] The Chan algorithm provides an upper bound of $O(n^{d/2})$ for *d* ≥ 3, so for *d* ≥ 3, it remains an open question whether faster algorithms are possible, or alternatively whether tighter lower bounds can be proven.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In particular, it remains open whether the algorithm's running time must depend on *d*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] In addition, the question of whether there are faster algorithms that can deal with special cases (for example, when the input coordinates are integers within a bounded range) remains open.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] The 1D Klee's measure problem (union of intervals) can be solved in $O(n\log p)$ where *p* denotes the number of piercing points required to stab all intervals (the union of intervals pierced by a common point can be calculated in linear time by computing the extrema).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/klee-s-measure-problem] Parameter *p* is an adaptive parameter that depends on the input configuration, and the piercing algorithm yields an adaptive algorithm for Klee's measure problem.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] This means that [*x*, *x′*] spans the whole interval from the left endpoint of Int(*v*1) to the right endpoint of Int(*v*3).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Note that all segments at a particular level are non-overlapping and ordered from left to right: this is true by construction for the level containing the leaves, and the property is not lost when moving from any level to the one above it by combining pairs of adjacent segments.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Now either parent(*v*2) = parent(*v*1), or the former is to the right of the latter (edges in the tree do not cross).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] In the first case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is the same as Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point; in the second case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is to the right of Int(parent(*v*1))'s rightmost point, and therefore also to the right of Int(*v*1)'s rightmost point.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] In both cases, Int(parent(*v*2)) begins at or to the right of Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Similar reasoning shows that Int(parent(*v*2)) ends at or to the left of Int(*v*3)'s rightmost point.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] Int(parent(*v*2)) must therefore be contained in [*x*, *x′*]; hence, [*x*, *x′*] will not be stored at *v*2.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces, in the form of multi-level segment trees.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] In higher dimensional versions, the segment tree stores a collection of axis-parallel (hyper-)rectangles, and can retrieve the rectangles that contain a given query point.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The structure uses *O*(*n* log*d* *n*) storage, and answers queries in *O*(log*d* *n*) time.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The use of fractional cascading lowers the query time bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/segment-tree] The use of the interval tree on the deepest level of associated structures lowers the storage bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] In computational geometry, a **sweep line algorithm** or **plane sweep algorithm** is an algorithmic paradigm that uses a conceptual *sweep line* or *sweep surface* to solve various problems in Euclidean space.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] It is one of the critical techniques in computational geometry.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] The idea behind algorithms of this type is to imagine that a line (often a vertical line) is swept or moved across the plane, stopping at some points.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] Geometric operations are restricted to geometric objects that either intersect or are in the immediate vicinity of the sweep line whenever it stops, and the complete solution is available once the line has passed over all objects.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] An application of the approach had led to a breakthrough in the computational complexity of geometric algorithms when Shamos and Hoey presented algorithms for line segment intersection in the plane in 1976.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] In particular, they described how a combination of the scanline approach with efficient data structures (self-balancing binary search trees) makes it possible to detect whether there are intersections among N segments in the plane in time complexity of O(*N* log *N*).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] The closely related Bentley–Ottmann algorithm uses a sweep line technique to report all K intersections among any N segments in the plane in time complexity of O((*N* + *K*) log *N*) and space complexity of O(*N*).
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] Since then, this approach has been used to design efficient algorithms for a number of problems in computational geometry, such as the construction of the Voronoi diagram (Fortune's algorithm) and the Delaunay triangulation or boolean operations on polygons.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] Topological sweeping is a form of plane sweep with a simple ordering of processing points, which avoids the necessity of completely sorting the points; it allows some sweep line algorithms to be performed more efficiently.
[src:sweep-line-paradigm/sweep-line-algorithm] The sweeping approach may be generalised to higher dimensions.
